http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 23 Jun 2018
Source: Food Safety News [edited]
http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2018/06/nc-restaurant-remains-open-while-e-coli-suspected-for-illnesses/#.WzAczYpOmhA


The Mexico Viejo restaurant in Taylorsville, NC, about 60 mi [approx. 96 km] north of Charlotte, [NC], remained open after as many as 45 customers reported illnesses to the local health department. Officials from the Alexander County Health Department said on [Fri 22 Jun 2018] that one _E. coli_ infection has been confirmed. One person was hospitalized due to the illness.

County health director Leeanne Whisnant said the health department was notified [Fri 22 Jun 2018] morning, about the confirmed case of _E. coli_. The health department issued a press release on the outbreak to local media and on Facebook that afternoon. She said at least 30 individuals have reported getting sick after eating chicken at the Mexico Viejo restaurant on [Wed 20 Jun 2018]. Most reported experiencing nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea within hours of eating at the restaurant located on Highway 90 East.

The health department sent environmental health specialists to the restaurant on [Fri 22 Jun 2018] and brought in the State Communicable Disease Branch and the State Environmental Health Division to work on the outbreak.

Anyone who ate at the Mexican restaurant on [Wed 20 Jun 2018] and who has since become ill should call the county health department at 828-632-9704. Anyone experiencing nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea should stay hydrated and seek medical attention if the symptoms become worse or do not subside, according to Whisnant.

If the illnesses remained linked to only [Wed 20 Jun 2018], Whisnant says the outbreak could be an isolated event. Alexander County has not had any multiple _E. coli_ cases in 20 years. At this point, dishes containing chicken served on [Wed 20 Jun 2018] are the suspected source of the illnesses. Those who've reported their illnesses to the Health Department also say they've recovered quickly.

